==Abstract==

This BIP defines the '''Mnemonic Descriptor''' (MD) format: an encoding for bitcoin wallet policies that is compact, error-correcting, and designed for hand-transcription onto durable media (paper, steel). Where BIP 39 standardizes the mnemonic encoding of HD seed entropy, MD standardizes the analogous encoding for the ''wallet structure'' — the BIP 388 wallet policy template, derivation paths, and (when needed) foreign extended public keys — such that the structural information necessary to reconstruct a wallet can survive independently of any digital archive.

The format consists of three layers: (a) a compact bytecode for BIP 380 output descriptors and BIP 388 wallet policies, extending the tag-based encoding pioneered by the public-domain <code>descriptor-codec</code> project; (b) a codex32-derived (BIP 93) encoding layer that reuses the bech32 alphabet and BCH error-correction polynomials but introduces a new human-readable part, header structure, and multi-string chunking for arbitrary-length payloads; and (c) a mandatory guided-recovery flow combining BCH ECC with structural knowledge to recover heavily damaged backups beyond the BCH limit.

==Motivation==

Bitcoin self-custody best practices require backing up the keys that control a wallet's funds. For wallets that use single-key or standard-path structures, BIP 39 provides a robust mnemonic backup: a 12- or 24-word phrase, typically engraved on metal, from which keys can be deterministically reconstructed when paired with the assumed standard derivation path.

This works for "vanilla" wallets, where the wallet structure (single-sig, BIP 44/49/84/86 path) is essentially conventional. For wallets with arbitrary spending policies expressed in miniscript — multisig, timelocks, decaying conditions, inheritance schemes — the policy structure itself becomes essential information that must be backed up, and the seed alone is insufficient. BIP 388 makes this explicit: a wallet policy that is not commonly understood "must be backed up alongside the seed... the recovery of the wallet would not be possible without it."

Existing approaches to policy backup are inadequate for the durable, engravable, decades-of-storage use case that BIP 39 mnemonics solve for seeds:

* '''JSON exports''' (Sparrow, Specter): not engravable; opaque to humans; verbose
* '''Encrypted descriptor files''' (Liana <code>.bed</code> format): not engravable; require digital infrastructure and the encryption password to decode; not human-readable
* '''Multisig configuration files''' (Coldcard, others): plaintext but several hundred bytes; multisig-only; no error correction
* '''Output descriptor strings''' (BIP 380 plain text): long; only a hash-based checksum suffix; not designed for hand transcription; embedding raw xpubs makes engraving impractical
* '''Bytewords / UR''' (Blockchain Commons): word-encoded and supports descriptors, but only CRC32 error detection (no correction); designed for QR transmission rather than engraved metal

What is missing is a format with the same robustness profile as BIP 39 — engravable, hand-transcribable, error-correcting, easily verified — but for ''wallet structure'' rather than seed entropy. This BIP defines that format.

MD is intentionally not a key-backup format. Seed phrases (BIP 39, SLIP 39) and codex32 (BIP 93) handle key material. MD handles the complementary problem: the policy template that connects keys into a wallet.

==Definitions and notation==

The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT", "SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this document are to be interpreted as described in [https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc2119 RFC 2119].

The following terms are used throughout this document:

* '''Wallet policy''' — a BIP 388 wallet policy: a wallet descriptor template plus an ordered key information vector.
* '''Template''' — the BIP 388 wallet descriptor template: a script structure containing <code>@i</code> placeholders in place of keys, with each placeholder followed by a derivation path expression.
* '''Placeholder''' (<code>@i</code>) — a numeric reference (e.g., <code>@0</code>, <code>@1</code>) inside a template that resolves to a specific key information entry.
* '''Key information''' — a serialized BIP 32 extended public key (xpub) prefixed with origin information of the form <code>[fingerprint/path]xpub</code>, as defined in BIP 388.
* '''Foreign xpub''' — an xpub belonging to the policy that is ''not'' derivable from any seed the user holds (typically a cosigner's key).
* '''Owned seed''' — a BIP 39, SLIP 39, codex32, or other seed for which the user has the recovery material.
* '''Template Card''' — an MD-encoded backup of a wallet's template, derivation paths, and (optionally) master fingerprints. Always required.
* '''Xpub Card''' — an MD-encoded backup of one foreign xpub with its origin information. Required only when the policy contains foreign xpubs (deferred to v1+; see "Versioning" below).
* '''Codex32''' — the BIP 93 encoding for hand-transcribed bitcoin secrets. MD reuses codex32's bech32 alphabet and BCH polynomials.
* '''bech32 alphabet''' — the 32-character set defined in BIP 173: <code>qpzry9x8gf2tvdw0s3jn54khce6mua7l</code>.
* '''Canonical bytecode''' — the unique, deterministic byte sequence produced by encoding a given wallet policy under the MD bytecode rules. Round-trip identity: <code>decode(encode(policy)) == policy</code> in canonical form.
* '''Chunk''' — one of one or more codex32-derived strings that together encode a single Template Card.

Bytes are written in hexadecimal as <code>0xNN</code>. Byte sequences are concatenated left-to-right in the order written. The bytecode layer is a packed bit stream (see §"Bytecode layer / General structure"); fixed-width bit fields are MSB-first, and variable-length integer fields use the LP4-ext varint encoding defined in §"LP4-ext varint". All character positions in encoded strings are 0-indexed.

==Format overview==

An MD backup of a wallet consists of one or more cards, where each card is a string of bech32 characters that can be engraved, transcribed, or otherwise stored on durable media. There are three card types:

# '''Template Card''' (this BIP, v0): encodes the wallet's template, derivation paths, and optional master fingerprints. Always required. May span one or more chunks.
# '''Xpub Card''' (deferred to v1+): encodes one foreign xpub with origin information. One per foreign xpub. Not specified in v0.
# '''Policy ID''' (optional): a short identifier derived from the canonical bytecode, used for cross-verifying digital copies of the policy against the engraved Template Card. May be stamped separately.

The v0 specification scope (this document) covers wallets where the user holds every seed referenced by the policy (no foreign xpubs) and all <code>@i</code> placeholders use a single shared derivation path. Wallets meeting these criteria require only a Template Card. Foreign xpubs and per-placeholder paths are deferred to a future version of this specification.

''See §"Top-level descriptor scope" for the normative allow-list and §"Frequently Asked Questions" for design choices.''

Forward compatibility is preserved: MD v0 readers MUST reject backups marked with newer version bytes (loud failure), and MD v1+ readers MUST accept v0 Template Cards (graceful upgrade).

==Top-level descriptor scope==

Conformant encoders MUST accept exactly the following top-level descriptor
templates as input:

* '''<code>wpkh(KEY)</code>''' — BIP 84 native-segwit single-sig.
* '''<code>wsh(SCRIPT)</code>''' — native-segwit script (multisig and miniscript
  script trees per BIP 388 wallet-policy grammar).
* '''<code>sh(wpkh(KEY))</code>''' — BIP 49 nested-segwit single-sig.
* '''<code>sh(wsh(SCRIPT))</code>''' — BIP 48/1' nested-segwit multisig. The
  inner SCRIPT is subject to the same constraints as a top-level <code>wsh</code>.
* '''<code>tr(KEY)</code>''' or '''<code>tr(KEY, TREE)</code>''' — BIP 86
  taproot: keypath-only, single-leaf, or multi-leaf script tree. <code>TREE</code>
  may be a single tap-leaf script or a recursively nested script tree using the
  <code>TapTree (0x05)</code> inner-node tag, subject to BIP 341's
  <code>TAPROOT_CONTROL_MAX_NODE_COUNT = 128</code> depth ceiling. See
  §"Taproot tree" for the bytecode form. Active (v0.5).

Conformant MD encoders MUST reject the following BIP-388-permitted top-level
forms; MD's accepted scope is narrower than BIP 388:

* '''<code>pkh(KEY)</code>''' — legacy P2PKH single-sig (BIP 388 admits; MD rejects)
* '''<code>sh(multi(K, ...))</code>''', '''<code>sh(sortedmulti(K, ...))</code>''',
  '''<code>sh(KEY)</code>''' — legacy P2SH (BIP 388 admits; MD rejects)
* '''<code>bare(SCRIPT)</code>''' — pre-2014 raw script (BIP 388 also excludes;
  MD inherits)

See §"Frequently Asked Questions: Why is MD narrower than BIP 388?" for the rationale.

Decoders MUST reject these forms with a structured error distinguishable from
generic checksum failure and from generic bytecode-parse failure. Reserved-tag
rejections are surfaced via <code>Error::TagOutOfRange</code>; tap-leaf scope
violations via <code>Error::ForbiddenTapTreeLeaf</code>; depth overflow via
<code>Error::DecodeRecursionDepthExceeded</code>. Pre-decode parser/walker
rejections (bare <code>SCRIPT</code>, unsupported top-level type, sh-inner
type mismatch) are reference-implementation-specific and surfaced at the
parse layer rather than the wire-decode layer. Cross-implementations MUST
reject the listed forms but MAY structure the diagnostic at parse vs decode
boundary as fits their architecture; the rejection SHOULD identify the
offending top-level type (or <code>sh(...)</code> inner type) so consumers
can disambiguate "top-level rejection" from "sh-inner rejection" from
"reserved-tag rejection".

All accepted forms follow the existing canonical form rules (no whitespace,
<code>/**</code> expansion, ascending placeholder order, <code>'</code> for
hardened). No type-specific canonicalization.

===Sh wrapper restriction matrix===

When a decoder consumes a top-level <code>sh</code> bytecode tag
(primary code <code>0x03</code>), the next bytecode tag determines admission:

{| class="wikitable"
|+ Tag values are 6-bit primary codes per the v0.30 bytecode wire format (see §"Tag table").
! Inner tag !! Inner type !! Action
|-
| <code>0x00</code> || <code>wpkh</code> || Decoder MUST recurse — admit as BIP 49 single-sig
|-
| <code>0x02</code> || <code>wsh</code> || Decoder MUST recurse — admit as BIP 48/1' multisig
|-
| Any other || any other || Decoder MUST reject with a structured error per §"Top-level descriptor scope"
|}

Decoders MUST peek the inner tag BEFORE recursive descent into the sh subtree.
This prevents recursion-bomb hostile inputs (e.g., <code>sh(sh(sh(...)))</code>
of arbitrary depth) — same hostile-input class as the malformed-payload-padding
defense in §"Payload".

===Default derivation paths===

When neither a caller-supplied path (Tier 0) nor a key-origin-extracted path (Tier 1) is available, encoders pick a per-top-level-type default path:

{| class="wikitable"
! Top-level !! Default path !! Reference
|-
| <code>wsh</code> || <code>m/48'/0'/0'/2'</code> || BIP 48 mainnet multisig P2WSH
|-
| <code>tr</code> || <code>m/86'/0'/0'</code> || BIP 86 mainnet (P2TR)
|-
| <code>wpkh</code> || <code>m/84'/0'/0'</code> || BIP 84 mainnet (P2WPKH)
|-
| <code>sh(wpkh)</code> || <code>m/49'/0'/0'</code> || BIP 49 mainnet (P2SH-P2WPKH)
|-
| <code>sh(wsh)</code> || <code>m/48'/0'/0'/1'</code> || BIP 48 mainnet multisig P2SH-P2WSH
|}

The path is encoded explicitly into the §"Origin path declaration" using the depth-prefixed component encoding; the v0.30 wire format does not carry a path dictionary, so a default path costs the same number of bits as any other path of the same depth.

==Specification==

===Encoding layer===

A single MD string is structured as:

<pre>
  <HRP> <separator> <header> <payload> <checksum>
</pre>

Each component is described below.

====Human-readable part====

The HRP is the two-character string <code>md</code> (lowercase) or <code>MD</code> (uppercase). HRP case MUST match the case of the data part. Mixed case within a single string is invalid and MUST be rejected.

Note: The chosen HRP is subject to formal SLIP-0173 registration (see FOLLOWUPS entry <code>slip-0173-register-md-hrp</code>). It was collision-vetted prior to adoption (see §"Why a new HRP?"). Implementations MUST use <code>md</code> until otherwise specified.

====Separator====

The separator is the single character <code>1</code>, following BIP 173 bech32 convention. The separator is excluded from the bech32 data alphabet and unambiguously marks the boundary between HRP and data.

====Header====

Each MD card's data part begins with a header that identifies the card mode, version, and (for chunked cards) reassembly information. The header is bit-packed at the front of the data part. Single-payload and chunked layouts are discriminated '''in-band''': decoders auto-dispatch on bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol (the <code>chunked</code> flag), with no caller hint. Single-payload headers carry <code>chunked = 0</code>; chunk headers carry <code>chunked = 1</code>. See §"Auto-dispatch and v0.x rejection" below for the discrimination trace.

For '''single-string Template Cards''' (the common case for small wallets), the header is 5 bits (one bech32 character) and matches the bytecode-layer payload header described in §"Bytecode header":

* Bit 4: divergent-paths flag.
* Bits 3–0: version (v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code> = 4). The 4-bit field absorbs the bit that v0.x reserved.

For '''chunked Template Cards''', the header is 37 bits (occupying eight bech32 characters with 3 bits of trailing slack absorbed by the symbol grid):

* Bits 36–33: version (v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code>). 4-bit field.
* Bit 32: chunked flag, MUST be <code>1</code>. This is the bit-0 discriminator of the first 5-bit symbol; auto-dispatch sees it before any other field.
* Bits 31–12: chunk-set identifier (CSI), 20 bits. A deterministic per-encoding identifier shared by all chunks of one Template Card, derived from the encoding's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> (defined immediately below). Used to detect chunks from different Template Cards being mixed during reassembly.
* Bits 11–6: total chunk count, 6 bits, encoded as <code>count − 1</code>. Range <code>1..64</code>. Encoders SHOULD use the smallest count that fits the payload.
* Bits 5–0: chunk index, 6 bits, 0-indexed. Range <code>0..(count − 1)</code>.

The chunk-set identifier is normatively bound to the canonical encoding. Define <code>Md1EncodingId</code> as the leading 16 bytes of <code>SHA-256</code> over the canonical bit-packed payload bytecode of the Template Card — the bytecode produced by the encoder for the assembled (single-string-equivalent) payload (see §"Payload" and §"Bytecode layer"). Encoders MUST derive <code>chunk_set_id</code> from <code>Md1EncodingId</code> by taking the leading 20 bits, MSB-first:

<pre>
  chunk_set_id = (Md1EncodingId[0] << 12) | (Md1EncodingId[1] << 4) | (Md1EncodingId[2] >> 4)
</pre>

This deterministic binding makes md1 encoding bit-reproducible — any two conforming encoders given the same canonical bytecode produce identical Template Card strings — and lets downstream toolchains SHA-pin regression corpora. Decoders MUST verify, after reassembly and bytecode decode, that the wire <code>chunk_set_id</code> matches the value derived from the reassembled encoding's <code>Md1EncodingId</code>; mismatch MUST be rejected with an error specifically identifying the chunk-set-id derivation check. The reference implementation surfaces this as <code>Error::ChunkSetIdMismatch { expected, derived }</code>.

<code>Md1EncodingId</code> is distinct from the Tier-3 <code>PolicyId</code> (§"Policy identifier") and from <code>WalletInstanceId</code> (§"Wallet Instance ID"): it covers the full Template Card payload (including any TLV blocks present in wallet-policy mode), whereas <code>PolicyId</code> covers only the BIP 388 template + path layout. The two values coincide for template-only cards but diverge once wallet-policy mode adds concrete pubkeys.

'''Naming note:''' the field was called "wallet identifier" in MD versions ≤ 0.8.x. The v0.8 rename (which renamed Tier-3 "wallet ID" → "Policy ID" — see §"Naming note" under "Policy ID" below for that rename's rationale) mechanically renamed this chunk-header field to ''ChunkPolicyId'' as collateral, but on review for the sibling Mnemonic Key (MK) format that name was misleading: the chunk-header field is neither a Policy ID (which lives at Tier 3 and identifies a policy template) nor a Wallet Instance ID (which identifies a template + xpub set); it identifies a chunk-set assembly and nothing more. v0.9 corrects the name to "chunk-set identifier" / <code>chunk_set_id</code>. Wire format and bit layout are unchanged across the v0.8 → v0.9 rename.

=====Auto-dispatch and safe rejection=====

Decoders dispatch between single-payload and chunked layouts by reading bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol:

* <code>bit 0 = 0</code> → single-payload mode; treat bits 4..1 as <code>paths</code> flag (bit 4) and version low bits (bits 3..1) and bit 0 as version's low bit <code>v0 = 0</code>.
* <code>bit 0 = 1</code> → chunked mode; treat bits 4..1 as the 4-bit version field, consume 32 more bits as chunk-header continuation.

The 4-bit version field has 16 representable values but the auto-dispatch constrains the usable subset: redesigned wire-format versions MUST have <code>v0 = 0</code> (even values), because <code>v0 = 1</code> would be mis-classified as chunked. Additionally <code>version = 0</code> collides with v0.x single-payload, and <code>version = 2</code> collides with v0.x chunked (which a v0.30 decoder reads as single-payload with version=2 — see below). The usable v0.30-family WF-redesign version set is therefore '''{4, 8, 12}'''. v0.30 uses <code>version = 4</code>; future major breaks would use 8 then 12.

v0.x payloads are rejected cleanly without silent mis-decode. The auto-dispatch trace:

{| class="wikitable"
! Input !! First 5 bits !! Decoder verdict
|-
| v0.x single-payload (version=0) || <code>[paths][0][0][0][0]</code> || bit 0 = 0 → single-payload; version = 0 → <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch { got: 0 }</code>
|-
| v0.x chunked (version=0, chunked=1) || <code>[0][0][0][1][0]</code> || bit 0 = 0 → single-payload; version = 2 → <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch { got: 2 }</code>
|-
| v0.30 single-payload || <code>[paths][0][1][0][0]</code> || bit 0 = 0 → single-payload; version = 4 → accepted
|-
| v0.30 chunked || <code>[0][1][0][0][1]</code> || bit 0 = 1 → chunked; version = 4 → accepted
|}

====Payload====

The payload is the canonical bit-packed bytecode (defined in §"Bytecode layer", below) of the Template Card, encoded directly as 5-bit codex32 symbols. For chunked Template Cards, each chunk's payload is one fragment of the assembled bit stream; chunking splits the bit stream into fragments at encoder-chosen bit boundaries (no byte-aligned framing).

The bytecode is bit-packed (MSB-first); 5-bit symbols are emitted directly from the bit stream with no intermediate byte-aligned conversion. The final symbol may carry up to 4 bits of trailing zero padding to align the bit count with the codex32 symbol grid.

Decoders MUST reject any MD string whose trailing-padding bits (after BCH checksum verification and bit-stream consumption by the decoder) are non-zero, except via the rollback-as-padding tolerance at the TLV-section boundary (§"TLV section / End-of-section detection"). Mid-stream non-zero pad bits cannot have been produced by a conforming encoder. The reference implementation surfaces this rejection as <code>Error::InvalidBytecode { kind: BytecodeErrorKind::MalformedPayloadPadding }</code>; cross-implementations MUST surface a semantically equivalent rejection — distinguishable from generic checksum failure and from generic bytecode-parse failure — so that conformance tests can pin the error path.

====Checksum====

The checksum is computed using a BCH error-correcting code with HRP-mixing applied in the BIP 173 style. The polymod algorithm is BIP 93's <code>ms32_polymod</code> (regular code) or <code>ms32_long_polymod</code> (long code), applied to the concatenation of:

# The HRP-expansion of <code>"md"</code>, computed exactly as in BIP 173 §"Bech32": for each HRP character <code>c</code> emit <code>ord(c) >> 5</code>; emit a single zero; for each HRP character emit <code>ord(c) & 31</code>. For the lowercase HRP <code>"md"</code> this yields the five 5-bit values <code>[3, 3, 0, 13, 4]</code> (length = 2 × len(HRP) + 1 = 5). Derivation: <code>ord('m') = 109 = 0x6d; 109 >> 5 = 3; 109 & 31 = 13</code>. <code>ord('d') = 100 = 0x64; 100 >> 5 = 3; 100 & 31 = 4</code>. The separator zero falls between the high-half list <code>[3, 3]</code> and the low-half list <code>[13, 4]</code>.
# The data part: header + payload as a sequence of 5-bit values from the bech32 alphabet.
# A pad of zero values during encoding (13 for regular, 15 for long) or the actual checksum during verification.

An MD string is valid when <code>polymod(input) == T_C</code>, where <code>T_C</code> is the target residue constant for the chosen code variant:

* '''Regular code''' (BCH(93,80,8)): for total data lengths up to and including 93 characters; checksum length: 13 characters. <code>T_REGULAR = 0x0815c07747a3392e7</code> (65 bits).
* '''Long code''' (BCH(108,93,8)): for total data lengths from 96 through 108 characters; checksum length: 15 characters. <code>T_LONG = 0x205701dd1e8ce4b9f47</code> (75 bits).

The derivation of <code>T_REGULAR</code> and <code>T_LONG</code> is documented in §"Why new target constants?" below.

A total data length of 94 or 95 characters is invalid. Encoders MUST NOT produce strings of these lengths. Decoders MUST reject them.

The choice of code (regular vs long) is determined by the actual data length after encoding. Encoders that produce a header + payload exceeding 93 characters MUST use the long code.

====Error-correction guarantees====

Both codes guarantee:

* Detection of any error pattern affecting up to 8 characters within a single string.
* Correction of up to 4 character substitutions.
* Correction of up to 8 erasures (positions known to be damaged).
* Correction of up to 13 (regular) or 15 (long) consecutive erasures (burst damage to a contiguous range of characters).

Detection of error patterns affecting more than 8 characters is probabilistic. The expected probability that a randomly damaged string of more than 8 errors decodes to a valid codeword is bounded by approximately 2<sup>−65</sup> (regular code) or 2<sup>−75</sup> (long code).

Conformant decoders MUST report which correction was applied (clean / N substitutions corrected / N erasures corrected / structure-aided / failed) per "Decoder reporting", below.

Implementations claiming v0.2-or-later support SHOULD use Berlekamp–Massey to derive the error-locator polynomial and Forney's algorithm to derive error magnitudes, working in the field <code>GF(1024) = GF(32)[ζ] / (ζ² − ζ − P)</code> with primitive elements <code>β = G·ζ</code> (regular code, order 93) and <code>γ = E + X·ζ</code> (long code, order 1023). The eight syndromes are computed at <code>{β<sup>77</sup>, …, β<sup>84</sup>}</code> for the regular code and <code>{γ<sup>1019</sup>, …, γ<sup>1026</sup>}</code> for the long code, matching the 8-consecutive-roots windows of the generator polynomial as specified in BIP 93 §"Generation of valid checksum". This canonical decoder makes the <code>Correction.corrected</code> values byte-identical across implementations on the same input. Alternative algorithms (e.g., brute-force enumeration up to <code>t = 4</code>) are permitted but MAY produce different but equally-valid corrections when multiple weight-≤ 4 codewords are equidistant from the received word; the canonical decoder breaks ties by ascending position index.

====Alphabet====

The data part (header + payload + checksum) uses the bech32 alphabet:

<pre>
  qpzry9x8gf2tvdw0s3jn54khce6mua7l
</pre>

This is the same 32-character set used by BIP 173 segwit addresses, BIP 350 bech32m, and BIP 93 codex32. The alphabet excludes <code>1</code>, <code>b</code>, <code>i</code>, <code>o</code>, and uppercase variants thereof to avoid common transcription confusables.

====Length envelope====

A codex32 character is one 5-bit symbol from the bech32 alphabet. The data part of a Template Card string consists of HRP + separator (3 characters) + payload bits + BCH checksum (13 characters for the regular code; 15 for the long code), with the total string length capped at 93 (regular) or 108 (long) characters.

For a single-string Template Card, the payload is the canonical bit-packed bytecode (5-bit header + origin-path-decl + use-site-path-decl + tree + TLV section), MSB-first, with up to 4 bits of trailing zero padding to align with the 5-bit codex32 symbol grid.

Maximum payload bits:
* Regular: (93 − 3 − 13) × 5 = 385 bits ≈ 48 bytes
* Long: (108 − 3 − 15) × 5 = 450 bits ≈ 56 bytes

For a chunked Template Card, each chunk's data part is HRP + separator (3 characters) + 37-bit chunk header (8 characters; 3 bits of trailing slack absorbed by the symbol grid) + fragment bits + checksum.

Maximum fragment bits per chunk:
* Regular: (93 − 3 − 8 − 13) × 5 − 3 = 342 bits
* Long: (108 − 3 − 8 − 15) × 5 − 3 = 407 bits

The −3 term subtracts the chunk-header's 3 bits of post-header symbol-grid slack. With up to 64 long-code chunks, a Template Card can carry approximately 64 × 407 ≈ 26,000 bits of assembled payload — far more than needed for any practical wallet policy. The v0.30 wire format does NOT carry a separate cross-chunk hash field; cross-chunk integrity is derived from the assembled-payload SHA-256 (see §"Chunking").

===Bytecode layer===

The bytecode is the canonical compact binary encoding of a wallet policy. It is the input to the encoding layer (above) and the output of decoding.

====General structure====

The bytecode is a packed bit stream — a contiguous concatenation of variable-width bit fields with no byte alignment between sections or operators. The bit stream is laid out MSB-first into bytes; the final byte is zero-padded if the total bit count is not a multiple of 8. The trailing zero-padding is also tolerated as up to 7 bits of slack at the TLV-section boundary (see §"TLV section / end-of-section detection") because the codex32 encoding layer emits 5-bit symbols.

A single-string Template Card carries the bytecode in this order:

# Header — 5 bits.
# Origin path declaration — variable.
# Use-site path declaration — variable, always present.
# Tree — variable, recursive.
# TLV section — variable, may be empty.

For chunked Template Cards, each chunk's bit stream begins with a 37-bit chunk header (carrying the chunk-set identifier, total chunk count, and this chunk's index) instead of the 5-bit payload header. The chunked and single-string layouts have distinguishable bit prefixes (see §"Header" and §"Chunking" for the full layouts) but the encoder/decoder dispatch is by reader role rather than by an in-band discriminator bit — see §"Header" for the rejection paths a mis-classifying decoder takes. After all chunks in a set are reassembled, the joined bit stream begins with the same 5-bit payload header and follows the same five-section layout above. Cross-chunk integrity is via the 20-bit chunk-set identifier carried in every chunk header (derived from the assembled payload's <code>Md1EncodingId</code>); see §"Chunking".

====Bytecode header====

The first 5 bits of the bytecode are the single-payload header:

{| class="wikitable"
! Bit !! Field !! Notes
|-
| 4 || Divergent-paths flag || <code>0</code> = a single shared origin path applies to every <code>@N</code> placeholder; <code>1</code> = one origin path per <code>@N</code> follows in the path declaration.
|-
| 3–0 || Version || 4-bit version field. v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code> (= 4). The 4-bit width absorbs the bit that v0.x reserved. Bit 0 doubles as the auto-dispatch discriminator (must be <code>0</code> for single-payload; see §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection"). Decoders MUST reject any other value with <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch { got }</code>; the future-usable WF-redesign set is <code>{4, 8, 12}</code> per the auto-dispatch constraint.
|}

The header occupies the first 5 bits of the bit stream MSB-first; the origin path declaration begins immediately at bit 5 with no padding.

====Origin path declaration====

The origin path declaration encodes the BIP 32 derivation path(s) that produce the xpubs referenced by each <code>@N</code> placeholder. The block dispatches on header bit 4:

{| class="wikitable"
! Mode !! Header bit 4 !! Wire layout
|-
| Shared || <code>0</code> || <code>[n: 5 bits, encoded n−1] [origin-path-encoding]</code>
|-
| Divergent || <code>1</code> || <code>[n: 5 bits, encoded n−1] [origin-path-encoding × n]</code>
|}

''n'' is the descriptor's key count, range <code>1..32</code> (BIP 388 placeholder cap), encoded as <code>n−1</code> in 5 bits. Out-of-range values are rejected with <code>Error::KeyCountOutOfRange { n }</code>. In divergent mode the path encodings appear in placeholder-index order: the first encoding applies to <code>@0</code>, the second to <code>@1</code>, and so on; there is no per-entry index field — position in the list IS the index.

Conforming encoders MUST examine the placeholder paths in placeholder-index order and emit shared mode (header bit 4 = 0) when all paths are equal, divergent mode (header bit 4 = 1) otherwise. This rule is a pure function of policy state; <code>encode(decode(encode(p)))</code> is bit-identical to <code>encode(p)</code>.

=====origin-path-encoding=====

Each origin-path-encoding is:

  <code>[depth: 4 bits] [component × depth]</code>

''depth'' is the number of BIP 32 derivation components in the path, range <code>0..15</code>. Decoders MUST reject <code>depth > 15</code> with <code>Error::PathDepthExceeded { got, max: 15 }</code>; encoders MUST symmetrically reject longer paths before serialization. The cap is defense-in-depth — no real-world BIP path family exceeds 6 components (BIP 48 + change/index = 6); 15 leaves generous headroom.

A path of depth <code>0</code> (the master node <code>m</code>) encodes as just the 4-bit zero-depth field with no following components.

The v0.30 wire format does not carry a path dictionary; every origin path is encoded explicitly using the depth-prefixed form above. (Historical context: pre-v0.11 versions carried a 1-byte indicator that selected between well-known BIP 44 / 48 / 84 / 86 / 87 paths and an explicit encoding; that mechanism was retired by the v0.11 wire-format reset and has never returned.)

=====component=====

Each component is:

  <code>[hardened: 1 bit] [value: LP4-ext varint]</code>

''hardened'' is the BIP 32 hardened bit. ''value'' is the un-hardened-bit child number, encoded as an LP4-ext varint (see §"LP4-ext varint", below). Component values up to <code>2^29 − 1</code> are representable; larger values are rejected with <code>Error::VarintOverflow { value }</code>.

=====Authority precedence with MK=====

When an MD card with per-<code>@N</code> paths participates in recovery alongside one or more MK cards (xpub backups; see [https://github.com/bg002h/mnemonic-key bg002h/mnemonic-key]), MK's <code>origin_path</code> is '''authoritative''' for the xpub's derivation; MD's per-<code>@N</code> path is '''descriptive''' — the policy's expected path layout. Per-format decoders are not required to be aware of cross-format context; consistency-checking is the recovery orchestrator's responsibility, and mismatch MUST cause the orchestrator to reject the assembly. See MK's BIP §"Authority precedence (MK ↔ MD path information)" for the full normative semantics.

====Use-site path declaration====

Following the origin path declaration is a use-site path declaration that encodes the BIP 388 multipath suffix (e.g. <code>/<0;1>/*</code>) shared by every <code>@N</code> placeholder. It is always present; its minimal form (no multipath, unhardened wildcard) is 2 bits.

  <code>[has-multipath: 1 bit]</code>
  <code>[if has-multipath:</code>
  <code>  [alt-count: 3 bits, encoded count−2; range 2..9]</code>
  <code>  [alternative × count]</code>
  <code>]</code>
  <code>[wildcard-hardened: 1 bit]</code>

''has-multipath'' is <code>1</code> if a parenthesized alternation (<code><a;b;...></code>) precedes the wildcard, <code>0</code> otherwise. ''alt-count'' is the number of alternatives, encoded as <code>count − 2</code> in 3 bits; permitted range is <code>2..9</code> (out-of-range rejected with <code>Error::AltCountOutOfRange { got }</code>). ''wildcard-hardened'' is <code>1</code> if the trailing wildcard is <code>*h</code>, <code>0</code> for <code>*</code>.

=====alternative=====

Each alternative is encoded the same way as a derivation-path component (§"component", above):

  <code>[hardened: 1 bit] [value: LP4-ext varint]</code>

The standard BIP 388 multipath form <code>/<0;1>/*</code> encodes as 16 bits: 1 (multipath present) + 3 (count = 2) + 5 (alt 0: unhardened, value 0) + 6 (alt 1: unhardened, value 1) + 1 (unhardened wildcard).

When a wallet policy needs different multipath suffixes per <code>@N</code>, the shared default declared here is overridden per placeholder by the <code>UseSitePathOverrides</code> TLV entry (see §"TLV section", below).

====Tree operators====

The wallet's script is encoded as a tree of operators. Each bytecode-layer operator is identified by a tag drawn from a '''6-bit primary code space''' (values <code>0x00</code>–<code>0x3F</code>); primary value <code>0x3F</code> is the extension prefix, in which case the next 4 bits carry an extension subcode (0x0–0xF). Primary values <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x3E</code> are reserved for future operator allocations within the semantic ranges of §"Tag table" below. The TLV section is a separate tag space at 5-bit width (see §"TLV tag allocations"); bytecode 6-bit and TLV 5-bit are distinct namespaces. The tag table below reflects the v0.30 wire format. The authoritative source is <code>crates/md-codec/src/tag.rs</code> in the reference implementation; the BIP table mirrors that mapping.

The wire format packs operator tags + their operand bits contiguously without byte alignment between operators (see §"General structure" above for the section ordering and §"Origin path declaration", §"Use-site path declaration", and §"TLV section" for the bit-aligned mechanisms that carry path-decl framing, per-<code>@N</code> origin-path overrides, fingerprints, and xpubs — none of which occupy slots in the operator-tag table below).

=====Tag table=====

Bytecode primary codes occupy a 6-bit space (values <code>0x00</code>–<code>0x3F</code>). Slots <code>0x00</code>–<code>0x23</code> are allocated to the 36 operators below; slots <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x3E</code> are reserved (decoder MUST reject with <code>Error::TagOutOfRange { primary }</code>); slot <code>0x3F</code> is the extension prefix followed by a 4-bit subcode (no extension subcodes are allocated in v0.30 — the entire 16-slot subspace is reserved).

