| 6 || Tree: <code>multi</code> tag || <code>000110</code> — primary tag <code>0x06</code>
|-
| 5 || Tree: <code>k − 1</code> || <code>00001</code> — threshold k = 2
|-
| 5 || Tree: <code>n − 1</code> || <code>00001</code> — child count n = 2
|-
| 1 || Tree: idx[0] || <code>0</code> — placeholder <code>@0</code> (kiw = 1)
|-
| 1 || Tree: idx[1] || <code>1</code> — placeholder <code>@1</code>
|-
| 0 || TLV section || empty (no fingerprints, no overrides)
|}

Section sums: 5 (header) + 37 (path-decl: 5+4+11+5+5+7) + 16 (use-site) + 24 (tree: <code>wsh</code>(6) + <code>multi</code>(6) + <code>k−1</code>(5) + <code>n−1</code>(5) + 2 × idx(1)) + 0 (TLV) = 82 bits. Note the multi-family body packs raw kiw-bit indices directly (no per-child tags) per §"Operator children layout"; this is the key v0.30 multi-family packing change relative to v0.x's per-child <code>pk_k</code> framing.

The same policy with a <code>Fingerprints</code> TLV entry binding <code>@0</code> to <code>0xdeadbeef</code> and <code>@1</code> to <code>0xcafebabe</code> is the 164-bit stream <code>2052d84212a00182182142f09bd5b7ddfcafebabe0</code> (21 bytes; 164 bits used, 4 bits trailing zero-padding). The first 82 bits are identical to the no-fingerprints encoding above; the trailing 82 bits are the <code>Fingerprints</code> TLV entry:

{| class="wikitable"
! Bits !! Field !! Decoded
|-
| 5 || TLV tag || <code>00001</code> — tag <code>0x01</code> (<code>Fingerprints</code>)
|-
| 11 || TLV length || LP4 varint encoding 66 (= 2 entries × (kiw + 32) = 2 × 33 bits); <code>0111 1000010</code> (L=7, payload <code>1000010</code>)
|-
| 1 || Entry 0 idx || <code>0</code> — placeholder <code>@0</code> (kiw = 1)
|-
| 32 || Entry 0 fingerprint || <code>deadbeef</code>
|-
| 1 || Entry 1 idx || <code>1</code> — placeholder <code>@1</code>
|-
| 32 || Entry 1 fingerprint || <code>cafebabe</code>
|}

====LP4-ext varint====

LP4-ext is the variable-length integer encoding used for path-component values, use-site-path alternative values, and TLV-length fields. Bit-aligned, MSB-first within each field.

  <code>single-form (L < 15):    [L: 4 bits] [payload: L bits]</code>
  <code>extension-form (L = 15): [L: 4 bits = 15] [L_high: 4 bits]</code>
  <code>                         [payload_low: 14 bits] [payload_high: L_high bits]</code>
  <code>                         total = (payload_high << 14) | payload_low</code>

In single-form, ''L'' bits of payload follow the 4-bit length prefix MSB-first. In extension-form (signaled by <code>L = 15</code>), an additional 4-bit ''L_high'' selects 1..15 extra payload bits beyond the 14-bit ''payload_low''; the full value is reassembled as <code>(payload_high << 14) | payload_low</code>. Total payload capacity is up to <code>14 + 15 = 29</code> bits, encoding values <code>0..2^29 − 1</code>. Out-of-range values are rejected with <code>Error::VarintOverflow { value }</code>.

Bit costs for representative values: <code>0</code> is 4 bits (L=0, no payload); <code>1</code> is 5 bits (L=1, 1-bit payload); <code>84</code> is 11 bits (L=7, 7-bit payload); <code>16383</code> is 18 bits (L=14, 14-bit payload, single-form boundary); <code>16384</code> is 23 bits (extension-form, L_high=1).

Note: LP4-ext applies to variable-range fields only — path-component values, use-site-path alternative values, and TLV length values. The <code>multi</code>, <code>sortedmulti</code>, <code>multi_a</code>, <code>sortedmulti_a</code>, and <code>thresh</code> threshold (<code>k − 1</code>) and count (<code>n − 1</code>) fields use '''fixed 5-bit''' encoding, NOT LP4-ext: bounded by the BIP 388 wallet-policy cap of ≤ 32 keys, fixed-5 is bit-efficient for every realistic value 1..31 (saves 11 bits across the 17-wallet validation corpus relative to LP4-ext throughout). Timelock values (<code>after</code>, <code>older</code>) are encoded as raw 32-bit fields per BIP 68 / BIP 113.

====Taproot tree====

The <code>tr()</code> operator (<code>0x01</code>) encodes a top-level taproot wallet policy. The internal-key sub-tree (a key reference) immediately follows the <code>tr()</code> tag. The optional script-tree position that follows is one of:

* Absent — keypath-only <code>tr(KEY)</code>; no further bytes in the operator payload.
* A single tap-leaf miniscript — encoded directly as a leaf-script tag sequence (any operator from the per-leaf miniscript subset detailed below in this section). This is the <code>tr(KEY, leaf)</code> form.
* A <code>TapTree</code> inner-node framing — a recursive <code>[TapTree=0x05][LEFT_SUBTREE][RIGHT_SUBTREE]</code> sequence where each <code>SUBTREE</code> is recursively defined as another tap-leaf or another inner-node framing. This is the <code>tr(KEY, TREE)</code> multi-leaf form. (Historical tag-value drift: <code>TapTree</code> was 0x08 in v0.5, renumbered to 0x07 in v0.6, renumbered to 0x05 in v0.11; the v0.30 6-bit primary tag space keeps 0x05.)

Multi-leaf taproot trees are encoded recursively using the <code>TapTree (0x05)</code> tag as inner-node framing. BIP 388's curly-brace source form <code>{LEFT, RIGHT}</code> is the human-readable counterpart of this bytecode; the MD bytecode is the wire encoding of that grammar.

The decoder enforces BIP 341's <code>TAPROOT_CONTROL_MAX_NODE_COUNT = 128</code> ceiling on tree depth via a peek-before-recurse pattern: a <code>0x05</code> tag is consumed only after the depth gate passes, so a hostile producer cannot blow the parser's stack via deeply nested framings. Decoders MUST reject trees that would exceed depth 128 with <code>Error::DecodeRecursionDepthExceeded { depth, max: 128 }</code>.

Implementations MAY enforce a per-leaf miniscript subset matching their target hardware signer's documented admit list. The MD encoding format itself does not require this — see §"Signer compatibility (informational)" below for the layered-responsibility framing. Implementations SHOULD clearly document any such limitations per BIP 388 §"Implementation guidelines".

=====Signer compatibility (informational)=====

The MD encoding format is neutral on hardware-signer compatibility. An MD-encoded backup of a BIP 388 wallet policy is structurally well-formed if and only if the policy parses under BIP 388 + BIP 379; whether the policy is signable on a particular hardware signer is a separate concern handled by tools above and below MD.

The responsibility chain is:

# Wallet software (e.g., Sparrow, Liana, Specter, Bitcoin Core) constructs a BIP 388 wallet policy. The wallet should know which signer the policy targets and produce shapes the signer admits.
# MD encodes the policy losslessly into engravable steel-backup form.
# The user, recovering the backup, decodes the MD string back into a BIP 388 policy.
# The recovery wallet pairs the policy with the matching signer and constructs spending transactions.

If an MD-encoded backup contains operators a recovery-time signer will not sign, recovery may require either a different signer or manual signing infrastructure (Bitcoin Core, custom signing pipelines).

Implementations MAY provide opt-in signer-subset validators as a layered concern. Such validators are tracked separately from this specification — see for example the named subsets maintained for Coldcard (firmware/edge <code>docs/taproot.md</code>) and Ledger (<code>LedgerHQ/vanadium</code> <code>apps/bitcoin/common/src/bip388/cleartext.rs</code>). A reference Rust implementation of the layered checker pattern ships as the <code>md-signer-compat</code> crate (workspace member alongside <code>md-codec</code>; v0.7.0+) with <code>COLDCARD_TAP</code> and <code>LEDGER_TAP</code> subsets, a <code>validate_tap_tree</code> walker that threads DFS-pre-order leaf indices through each per-leaf check, and a <code>md-signer-compat validate --signer &lt;name&gt; ...</code> CLI binary.

=====Bit-layout examples=====

The four representative taproot shapes below are sourced from the reference implementation (verifiable via <code>md encode</code> + <code>md bytecode</code>). For each shape, the table walks the tree portion of the bit stream; the header, origin-path-decl, and use-site-path-decl bit-counts are summarized but not redrawn (they share the same shape as the §"Bit-layout example" walkthrough above, parameterized only by ''n'' and the chosen origin path).

'''Key-path-only <code>tr(@0/<0;1>/*)</code>''' with origin path <code>m/86'/0'/0'</code>, ''n'' = 1, key-index width <code>kiw</code> = 0.
* Phrase: <code>md1yq80tgggqpsyn7sts50y35ujk</code>
* Bytecode: <code>200ef5a108006040</code> (8 bytes; 60 bits used)
* Header (5) + path-decl (31) + use-site (16) + tree (8) = 60 bits
* Tree (8 bits): <code>000001 0 0</code> — <code>tr</code> tag <code>0x01</code> (6 bits); <code>is_nums</code> = 0 (1 bit); <code>key_index</code> = (suppressed, kiw = 0); <code>has_tree</code> = 0 (no script tree)

'''Single-leaf <code>tr(@0/<0;1>/*, pk(@1/<0;1>/*))</code>''' with origin path <code>m/48'/0'/0'/2'</code>, ''n'' = 2, ''kiw'' = 1.
* Phrase: <code>md1ypfdsssj5qqczf2s3zwfsvk6dgpe</code>
* Bytecode: <code>2052d84212a001812540</code> (10 bytes; 74 bits used)
* Header (5) + path-decl (37) + use-site (16) + tree (16) = 74 bits
* Tree (16 bits): <code>000001 0 0 1 [001010 1]</code> — <code>tr</code> tag (6); <code>is_nums</code> = 0 (1); <code>key_index</code> = 0 (kiw = 1); <code>has_tree</code> = 1 (1); leaf <code>pk_k(@1)</code> as a bare <code>PkK</code> node (6-bit tag <code>0x0A</code> + 1-bit <code>key_index</code> = 1). Tap-leaves do NOT carry the <code>c:</code> wrapper around <code>pk_k</code> that wsh-context BIP 388 sugar emits — the BIP 388 <code>pk(K)</code> sugar expansion is context-aware, and tap-leaves emit <code>PkK</code> directly per §"Round-trip canonical form".

'''Single-leaf <code>tr(@0/<0;1>/*, multi_a(2, @1/<0;1>/*, @2/<0;1>/*, @3/<0;1>/*))</code>''' with origin path <code>m/48'/0'/0'/2'</code>, ''n'' = 4, ''kiw'' = 2.
* Phrase: <code>md1yrfdsssj5qqczyszymq8hhdwdr8038m</code>
* Bytecode: <code>20d2d84212a00181120226c0</code> (12 bytes; 90 bits used)
* Header (5) + path-decl (37) + use-site (16) + tree (32) = 90 bits
* Tree (32 bits): <code>000001 0 00 1 [001000 00001 00010 01 10 11]</code> — <code>tr</code> tag (6); <code>is_nums</code> = 0 (1); <code>key_index</code> = 0 (kiw = 2); <code>has_tree</code> = 1 (1); leaf <code>multi_a</code> (6-bit tag <code>0x08</code>) with <code>k − 1</code> = 1 (5 bits), <code>n − 1</code> = 2 (5 bits), then three raw kiw-bit indices = 1, 2, 3 (multi-family raw-index packing per §"Operator children layout"; no per-child tags).

'''Two-leaf TapTree <code>tr(@0/<0;1>/*, {pk(@1/<0;1>/*), pk(@2/<0;1>/*)})</code>''' with origin path <code>m/48'/0'/0'/2'</code>, ''n'' = 3, ''kiw'' = 2.
* Phrase: <code>md1yzfdsssj5qqczy22f2ad62s0r5ju6z9</code>
* Bytecode: <code>2092d84212a00181114a4a80</code> (12 bytes; 90 bits used)
* Header (5) + path-decl (37) + use-site (16) + tree (32) = 90 bits
* Tree (32 bits): <code>000001 0 00 1 [000101 [001010 01] [001010 10]]</code> — <code>tr</code> tag (6); <code>is_nums</code> = 0 (1); <code>key_index</code> = 0 (kiw = 2); <code>has_tree</code> = 1 (1); then <code>TapTree</code> inner node (6-bit tag <code>0x05</code>) with two child sub-trees: left = <code>pk_k(@1)</code> (6 + 2 = 8 bits), right = <code>pk_k(@2)</code> (6 + 2 = 8 bits). Deeper TapTree nesting recursively chains additional <code>0x05</code> framings up to the BIP 341 depth-128 ceiling (also enforced by the decoder via <code>MAX_DECODE_DEPTH = 128</code>).

For the BIP-341 NUMS H-point key-path-only form (<code>tr(NUMS, ...)</code>), the body's leading <code>is_nums</code> bit is set and the <code>key_index</code> field is suppressed entirely on the wire. The descriptor's tree omits any internal-key placeholder. See §"<code>tr()</code> NUMS encoding" above for the canonicalization invariant; concrete worked NUMS examples can be regenerated via <code>md compile --context tap '...'</code> in the reference implementation when built with the <code>cli-compiler</code> feature.

====Round-trip canonical form====

An MD-encoded Template Card MUST round-trip losslessly with the BIP 388 wallet policy string in canonical form. Canonical form requires:

* No optional whitespace anywhere in the policy string.
* Multipath shorthand <code>/**</code> is expanded to <code>/&lt;0;1&gt;/*</code> in canonical form.
* The key information vector is ordered by ascending placeholder index, with <code>@0</code> first.
* Hardened path components use the <code>'</code> character (not <code>h</code> or <code>H</code>).

Encoders MUST produce canonical form. Decoders MUST accept canonical form and SHOULD accept the equivalent non-canonical forms above (normalizing on decode). Decoders MAY reject other non-canonical inputs (e.g., re-ordered key vectors that don't match placeholder indices).

'''Walker normalization invariant.''' At every key-check position the canonical wire shape is a bare <code>Tag::PkK</code> (or <code>Tag::PkH</code>) — <code>Tag::Check</code> is NEVER emitted wrapping a key leaf. The renderer reconstructs the <code>c:</code> wrapper at output time for canonical BIP 388 rendering of <code>c:pk_k(K)</code> / <code>c:pk_h(K)</code> (or the BIP 379 sugar <code>pk(K)</code> / <code>pkh(K)</code>). <code>Tag::Check</code> remains valid on the wire only when wrapping a non-key child. This eliminates per-c:-position duplication, saving ~5 bits per key-check site.

===Chunking===

When a Template Card's canonical bytecode exceeds the maximum payload of a single long-code codex32 string, the encoding MUST be chunked. Encoders MAY also chunk smaller bytecodes for ergonomic reasons (e.g., to fit on physical media) but SHOULD prefer single-string encoding when the payload fits.

====Chunk header (37 bits)====

Each chunk is a complete codex32-derived string. In place of the 5-bit payload header used by single-string Template Cards (§"Bytecode header"), each chunk's bit stream begins with a 37-bit chunk header. The first 5-bit symbol carries the auto-dispatch discriminator at bit 0 (<code>chunked = 1</code>); see §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection".

{| class="wikitable"
! Bits !! Field !! Notes
|-
| 36–33 || Version || 4-bit version. v0.30 = <code>0b0100</code> (= 4). Usable WF-redesign set is <code>{4, 8, 12}</code> per §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection".
|-
| 32 || Chunked flag || MUST be <code>1</code> in chunk headers. This is bit 0 of the first 5-bit codex32 symbol; auto-dispatch reads it before any other field. The single-payload header carries <code>chunked = 0</code> at the same bit position (which is the low bit <code>v0</code> of its version field).
|-
| 31–12 || Chunk-set identifier (CSI) || 20 bits. Derived from the assembled payload's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> (top 20 bits of <code>SHA-256</code> over the canonical bit-packed payload, MSB-first). Identical across all chunks in a set; functions as the cross-chunk integrity anchor.
|-
| 11–6 || Count − 1 || Total chunks in the set, range <code>1..64</code>, encoded as <code>count − 1</code> in 6 bits. Out-of-range rejected with <code>Error::ChunkCountOutOfRange</code>.
|-
| 5–0 || Index || This chunk's zero-based index within the set, in 6 bits. MUST be less than ''count''; out-of-range rejected with <code>Error::ChunkIndexOutOfRange</code>.
|}

====Chunk fragment====

After the 37-bit chunk header, each chunk carries an arbitrary fragment of the assembled payload's bit stream. Encoders SHOULD divide the canonical payload bit stream into fragments of approximately equal size; the exact division is implementation-defined, provided each chunk's bit-stream length fits within the codex32 size envelope chosen for the chunk's BCH code (regular or long). Decoders MUST accept any valid division. The boundary between header and fragment is exactly bit 37; the fragment runs from bit 37 to the end of the chunk's payload bits.

The chunk-set identifier serves the cross-chunk integrity role that a separate appended hash served in earlier wire formats. Because the CSI is derived from the assembled-payload SHA-256, an encoder that draws a non-conforming CSI produces a string whose CSI cannot be reproduced by a conforming decoder; mismatch is detected at reassembly (see below). v0.30 does NOT carry a separate cross-chunk hash field.

====Reassembly====

Decoders reassemble a chunked Template Card by:

# Collecting all chunks transcribed by the user.
# Verifying all chunks share the same 20-bit chunk-set identifier; reject if mixed.
# Verifying all chunks declare the same total chunk count; reject if inconsistent.
# Sorting chunks by chunk index; reject if any index appears multiple times or is missing.
# Verifying the highest index equals (count − 1); reject if not.
# Concatenating each chunk's fragment bits in index order to reconstruct the canonical payload bit stream.
# Decoding the assembled payload as a Template Card (5-bit header at bit offset 0, then the standard five-section layout).
# Computing <code>Md1EncodingId</code> from the canonical bit-packed re-encoding of the decoded Template Card and verifying that the chunk-headers' wire chunk-set identifier matches the value derived from <code>Md1EncodingId</code> per §"Chunk header"; reject on mismatch with an error specifically identifying the derivation check (the reference implementation surfaces this as <code>Error::ChunkSetIdMismatch</code>). This ratifies that the encoder followed the deterministic-CSI contract; a non-conforming encoder that drew a random value would produce a string unreadable by conforming decoders.

===Policy identifier (Tier 3)===

A Policy ID is a derived identifier MAY be engraved on a separate medium for offline cross-verification of a digital backup of the policy against the engraved Template Card. The Policy ID is computed as:

<pre>
  policy_id = SHA-256(canonical_bytecode)[0..16]
</pre>

The first 16 bytes of the SHA-256 of the canonical bytecode (the same bit-packed payload that is encoded as the Template Card; the chunk-set identifier carried in chunk headers is derived from the same hash, see §"Chunking"). Policy IDs are encoded as 12-word BIP 39 mnemonic phrases (128 bits, including a 4-bit checksum word).

A Policy ID is OPTIONAL and never required for recovery from the Template Card alone. It serves only as a cryptographic anchor for verifying that a supplemental digital copy of the policy is authentic.

'''Engraving — MAY, not SHOULD.''' The 12-word PolicyId phrase MAY be engraved on a separate metal anchor for offline cross-verification with a digital backup of the codex32 string. Users who maintain only the codex32 Template Card itself need not engrave the phrase — the codex32 string carries the policy directly with BCH error correction; the phrase is a redundant integrity check rather than a recovery primitive. For users who want a minimal-cost identifier, the '''PolicyId fingerprint''' (top 4 bytes of <code>PolicyId</code>, rendered as 8 lowercase hex characters, parallel to BIP 32 master-key fingerprints) is offered as an 8-character display form. The reference implementation exposes this as <code>PolicyId::fingerprint() -> [u8; 4]</code> (v0.10+).

'''Naming note:''' the value previously called "wallet ID" was renamed to "Policy ID" in v0.8 to reflect what it actually identifies. The 16-byte hash covers the BIP 388 wallet-policy ''template'' (with <code>@N</code> placeholders) but not the concrete cosigner xpubs that map placeholders to keys. Two distinct wallets that share an identical policy template (same multisig shape and shared path, different cosigner sets) therefore share a Policy ID. The Policy ID is a ''template-level'' identifier; the per-instance cryptographic identifier is the Wallet Instance ID defined below.

====PolicyId types (Type 0 / Type 1)====

MD defines two cryptographic wallet-identifying hashes at different levels of specificity. We refer to them as '''types of PolicyId''' for ease of reference:

* '''Type 1 — <code>PolicyId</code>.''' <code>SHA-256(canonical_bytecode)[0..16]</code>. Identifies the wallet ''template + path layout'': the BIP 388 script structure plus the per-<code>@N</code> origin paths (which for v0.x ≤ 0.9 was a single shared path; for v0.10+ admits per-<code>@N</code> paths). Two wallets with the same template and same path layout but ''different'' concrete cosigner xpubs share a Type-1 <code>PolicyId</code>. Engraved as the optional 12-word BIP 39 phrase (see "Engraving — MAY, not SHOULD" above).
* '''Type 0 — <code>WalletInstanceId</code>.''' <code>SHA-256(canonical_bytecode || canonical_xpub_serialization)[0..16]</code>. Identifies the wallet ''instance'': template + paths + concrete cosigner xpubs. Two wallets are distinct even if they share a template and path layout, as long as their cosigner xpub sets differ. Computed at recovery time from policy + assembled xpubs; not engraved on any physical card. See §"Wallet Instance ID" below.

Type 1 answers "what shape of wallet is this?"; Type 0 answers "which specific wallet instance is this?" Type 1 is the engraved anchor (Tier 3, MAY-engrave). Type 0 is the cryptographic check at recovery time. The two are not interchangeable: a Type-1 collision is expected and acceptable (two cosigners' wallets sharing a multisig shape); a Type-0 collision would indicate identical wallet instances. The reference implementation's <code>PolicyId</code> Rust type carries the Type-1 semantics; <code>WalletInstanceId</code> the Type-0; the names carry the type so no separate <code>Type1PolicyId</code> / <code>Type0PolicyId</code> aliases are introduced.

'''Path-divergence injectivity.''' Two policies with the same script template but different per-cosigner accounts (e.g., one cosigner on BIP 48 account 0' vs the same wallet on account 1') hash to ''different'' Type-1 <code>PolicyId</code>s in v0.10+ — they are different wallet shapes. In v0.x ≤ 0.9 such policies silently collided on Type-1 <code>PolicyId</code> because the canonical bytecode lossily flattened them to a single shared path. v0.10 closed that collision via the per-<code>@N</code> divergent-path encoding (originally byte-aligned <code>Tag::OriginPaths = 0x36</code>; replaced in v0.11 by the divergent-paths header bit and the bit-aligned origin-path-encoding described in §"Origin path declaration"). The bug fix is preserved across both encoding mechanisms; the divergent-path Type-1 <code>PolicyId</code> for such wallets in v0.10+ differs from the (incorrect, lossily-computed) v0.9 <code>PolicyId</code>. Users who computed PolicyIds on divergent-path policies under v0.x ≤ 0.9 SHOULD re-engrave under v0.10+.

===Wallet Instance ID===

A Wallet Instance ID is a derived 16-byte identifier that distinguishes wallets sharing an identical policy template but differing in their cosigner xpub set. Unlike the Policy ID, the Wallet Instance ID is '''not''' carried by any physical card — it is a recovery-time computation. Tools that have the policy card (template) plus the cosigner xpubs (whether from a digital backup, the wallet itself, or — in foreign-xpub multisig — engraved <code>mk1</code> key cards) compute it on demand:

<pre>
  wallet_instance_id = SHA-256(canonical_bytecode || canonical_xpub_serialization)[0..16]
</pre>

where:

<pre>
  canonical_xpub_serialization = concat(
      bip32_serialize(xpub_for_@0),
      bip32_serialize(xpub_for_@1),
      ...
      bip32_serialize(xpub_for_@(N-1))
  )
</pre>

<code>bip32_serialize</code> is the canonical 78-byte BIP 32 serialization of an extended public key (the binary form of a Base58Check-decoded xpub). Xpubs are concatenated in placeholder-index order (<code>@0</code>, then <code>@1</code>, ..., <code>@(N-1)</code>); ordering is significant. <code>canonical_bytecode</code> is the Template Card's bytecode, identical to the input of the Policy ID computation.

Wallet Instance IDs are useful for recovery tools that need to disambiguate same-template wallets, for downstream consistency between cross-tool implementations, and for digital-backup verification at the per-instance level. The construction does not introduce any new Tier-3 anchor; the existing 12-word Policy ID mnemonic anchor remains the only optional physical-medium anchor in the spec (and even that anchor is MAY-engrave, not SHOULD-engrave; see §"Policy identifier (Tier 3)").

===Decoder requirements===

Conformant MD decoders MUST:

# Recognize the MD HRP and reject any other HRP.
# Reject mixed-case strings.
# Auto-dispatch single-payload vs chunked by reading bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol (§"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection"); reject WF-version mismatch cleanly.
# Reject reserved-range tag values and structurally-invalid operator-context positions per the error taxonomy below.
# Implement BCH error correction for both regular and long codes per the polynomials specified above.
# Implement erasure-aware decoding when the user supplies known-bad positions.
# Verify the chunk-set identifier on reassembled chunks (compute <code>Md1EncodingId</code> from the assembled payload and reject if its top 20 bits differ from the chunk headers' wire <code>chunk_set_id</code>).
# Validate the bytecode against the tag table; reject unknown tags or malformed structure.
# Round-trip with BIP 388 canonical form.

Decoders SHOULD:

# Implement structure-aware candidate filtering during recovery (see "Guided recovery", below).
# Provide informational reporting on every decode attempt.
# Display the bech32 alphabet and example characters during user transcription.

====Error taxonomy====

Conformant decoders MUST distinguish the following structurally-defined error categories. The reference implementation surfaces each as a distinct <code>Error</code> variant in <code>crates/md-codec/src/error.rs</code>; cross-implementations MUST surface semantically equivalent categories so conformance test suites can pin error paths.

{| class="wikitable"
! Error !! Trigger
|-
| <code>WireVersionMismatch { got: u8 }</code> || Single-payload or chunked version field ≠ accepted v0.30 value (4 in this release). Per the auto-dispatch trace, v0.x payloads surface here cleanly.
|-
| <code>MalformedHeader { detail }</code> || Chunked-flag inconsistent with caller context; chunk-header fields out of range; chunk-header version mismatched with payload version.
|-
| <code>TagOutOfRange { primary: u8 }</code> || 6-bit primary in reserved range <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x3E</code>; primary <code>0x3F</code> extension prefix with any subcode (no extension subcodes allocated in v0.30).
|-
| <code>Codex32DecodeError(String)</code> || BCH verify returns false (HRP mismatch, uncorrectable transcription error, wrong format) or any other codex32-layer failure surfaced by the underlying decoder.
|-
| <code>OperatorContextViolation { tag, context: ContextKind }</code> || Tag in a forbidden position. <code>ContextKind</code> enum: <code>TopLevel</code> (e.g., bare <code>PkK</code> as top-level descriptor), <code>TapLeaf</code> (e.g., <code>Multi</code> instead of <code>MultiA</code> inside a tap leaf), <code>MultiBody</code> (non-key tag appearing where the multi-family raw kiw-bit index stream is expected). Decoder enforces the <code>TopLevel</code> check at <code>decode_payload</code>; raised when the root tag is outside the wrapper-tag allow-list <code>{Sh, Wsh, Wpkh, Pkh, Tr}</code> (since v0.31.0). <code>TapLeaf</code> is covered by the narrower <code>ForbiddenTapTreeLeaf</code> for BIP-342 leaf restrictions; <code>MultiBody</code> is structurally unreachable in v0.30+ encodings.
|-
| <code>NUMSSentinelConflict</code> || Inside <code>tr()</code> body: <code>is_nums = 0</code> with <code>key_index ≥ n</code>. (Field name is historical from the v0.18 sentinel design; v0.30 surfaces the same logical condition under the explicit-flag encoding.)
|-
| <code>DecodeRecursionDepthExceeded { depth, max }</code> || Recursion depth ≥ 128.
|-
| <code>PlaceholderIndexOutOfRange { idx, n }</code> || Key index ≥ <code>n</code> in non-<code>tr()</code> context (or in any <code>idx</code> field of a multi-family body / TLV entry).
|-
| <code>PathDepthExceeded { got, max }</code> || Path depth (origin or use-site) exceeds the spec's `MAX_PATH_COMPONENTS = 15` cap.
|-
| <code>KGreaterThanN { k, n }</code> || Multi-family or Thresh body decoded with <code>k > n</code>.
|-
| <code>TlvOrderingViolation { prev, current }</code> || TLV entries in non-ascending tag order.
|-
| <code>ChunkSetIdMismatch { expected, derived }</code> || After reassembling a chunked payload, the chunk-set-id declared by the chunks doesn't match the SHA-256-derived id of the reassembled payload.
|}

===Decoder reporting===

For every decode attempt, conformant decoders MUST report:

{| class="wikitable"
! Field !! Values !! Notes
|-
| Outcome || clean / auto-corrected / erasure-corrected / structure-aided / failed || Required
|-
| Errors corrected || integer 0–N, with positions || Required when applicable
|-
| Correction method || which technique succeeded || Required
|-
| Verification status || which post-decode checks passed || Required (chunk-set-identifier check for multi-chunk decodes, seed-derived xpub match, blockchain history if performed)
|-
| Confidence || Confirmed / High / Probabilistic / Failed || Required (see "Recovery confidence", below)
|}

A decoder MUST NOT report "Confirmed" confidence unless ALL of:

* BCH decode succeeded with at most 4 errors corrected total
* Chunk-set identifier verified (if multi-chunk)
* All <code>@i</code> placeholders matched user's seeds at recovered paths
* User explicitly confirmed the recovered policy structure matches expectation

Lower confidence levels MUST be reported with specific qualifiers identifying which guarantees did not hold.

===Guided recovery===

A guided recovery flow is REQUIRED in any MD-conformant tool. The flow combines BCH ECC, erasure decoding, user-supplied structural knowledge, and seed-derived xpub verification to recover damaged backups.

The flow MUST proceed through these stages, in order:

# '''Damage assessment.''' Accept the user's transcribed string(s). Display per-position character status. Allow user to mark positions as unreadable (erasures).
# '''Standard decode.''' Attempt BCH decoding with no user input. If successful, report and stop.
# '''Erasure-aware decode.''' If standard decode fails and erasures are marked, attempt erasure decoding (up to 8 erasures per string). If successful, report and stop.
# '''Structure elicitation.''' If decoding still fails, prompt the user for structural information they remember about the policy: wallet kind, key count, threshold, derivation path, timelock values, chunk-set identifier (if separately stamped).
# '''Constrained candidate search.''' Encode the user's structural assertions as a partial bytecode template. Enumerate candidate codewords within an extended Hamming radius (up to ~12) that decode to valid MD bytecode AND match the user's assertions.
# '''Candidate verification.''' For each surviving candidate, derive xpubs from available seeds at the candidate's declared paths, verify they map to the expected placeholders, verify the chunk-set identifier if multi-chunk, and reject candidates failing any check.
# '''Optional blockchain verification.''' With explicit user consent, derive the candidate's first N receive addresses and check on-chain history. Disclose privacy implications before this step.
# '''Result presentation.''' Display the recovered wallet policy in BIP 388 form, the Policy ID, derived xpubs, and the confidence level per "Decoder reporting".

Tools MUST disclose privacy implications before any blockchain query and SHOULD default to offline operation. Tools MUST NOT transmit recovered policy material to external services without explicit user consent.

==Rationale==

===Why a new format?===

Existing engravable formats (BIP 39, codex32) target seeds (uniformly random fixed-length entropy). Neither has framing for arbitrary structured data, and neither encodes wallet structure. Bytewords / UR encodes descriptors but with weak (CRC32) error correction and verbose output. <code>descriptor-codec</code> compactly encodes descriptors but produces raw bytes designed for QR/NFC, not engraving. No existing format combines a compact descriptor encoding with strong BCH error correction in a hand-transcribable form. MD fills this gap.

===Why codex32-derived encoding?===

Codex32 (BIP 93) is purpose-built for hand-transcribed bitcoin secrets. Its bech32 alphabet excludes visually confusable characters; its BCH polynomials provide strong error correction with mathematically guaranteed bounds; reference implementations exist; the encoding scheme is well-reviewed.

However, codex32's HRP is fixed to <code>ms</code> and its header structure is hard-coded for BIP 32 master seeds (Shamir threshold and identifier fields). Codex32 has no extensibility mechanism for non-seed payloads. MD therefore reuses codex32's '''cryptographic primitives''' (alphabet, BCH polynomials) but defines its own HRP and header structure, treating codex32 as a building block rather than a host format. This is consistent with how BIP 350 (bech32m) reused BIP 173's primitives with a different generator constant.

===Why a new HRP?===

A new HRP (<code>md</code>) is required because:
* Codex32's <code>ms</code> HRP cannot be reused without breaking codex32's seed-payload semantics.
* The bech32 checksum is computed over the HRP, providing domain separation: a damaged MD string cannot be misinterpreted as a bech32 address or codex32 seed share.
* The HRP serves as format self-identification for human readers and parsers.

The two-character HRP <code>md</code> was chosen as a compact, readable abbreviation of "Mnemonic Descriptor". It was verified clean against the SLIP-0173 registry, Lightning HRPs, Liquid sidechain HRPs, Codex32 (<code>ms</code>), Nostr NIP-19 HRPs, and Cosmos chain HRPs prior to adoption.

===Why new target constants?===

The target residue constants <code>T_REGULAR</code> and <code>T_LONG</code> are derived NUMS-style ("Nothing Up My Sleeve") as truncations of <code>SHA-256("shibbolethnums")</code> to 65 and 75 bits respectively, taking the most significant bits of the hash interpreted as a big-endian 256-bit integer.

The string <code>shibbolethnums</code> combines this proposal's working name during early development with the conventional <code>nums</code> suffix used in cryptographic constructions to indicate that the value was chosen via a public hash and not through opaque selection. The string itself is the audit trail: any reader can recompute the SHA-256 and verify that the constants follow from it.

We chose new constants rather than reusing BIP 93's <code>MS32_CONST</code> values for two reasons. First, although the HRP-mixing recipe (BIP 173 <code>hrp_expand</code>) produces residues that differ between any two HRPs sharing this polynomial, picking distinct target constants provides residue-level separation as well: damage that maps an MD string toward codex32-style validity is statistically prevented by the combination. Second, signaling matters — reusing codex32's specific target constant verbatim would invite the misreading that MD is "codex32 with a different HRP" rather than a distinct format that borrows codex32's polynomial.

The constants are reproducible by any SHA-256 implementation:

<source lang="python">
import hashlib
h = hashlib.sha256(b"shibbolethnums").digest()
T_REGULAR = int.from_bytes(h, 'big') >> (256 - 65)  # = 0x0815c07747a3392e7
T_LONG    = int.from_bytes(h, 'big') >> (256 - 75)  # = 0x205701dd1e8ce4b9f47
</source>

===Why descriptor-codec for the bytecode?===

<code>descriptor-codec</code> is a public-domain (CC0-1.0) Rust library that encodes BIP 380 output descriptors using a compact tag-based format with claimed 30–40% size reduction relative to plaintext. Its tag table covers all miniscript fragments and produces deterministic round-tripping bytecode. MD extends this with BIP 388 wallet-policy framing (<code>@i</code> placeholders), shared-path declarations, and a path dictionary, but reuses the underlying tag values for compatibility.

This design choice means: (a) MD does not invent a new bytecode for descriptors that are already correctly handled by an existing public-domain implementation; (b) implementations of MD that wish to also handle inline-key descriptors (a v1+ extension) can do so by adopting the existing reserved tags; (c) the MD extensions MAY be upstreamed into <code>descriptor-codec</code> if the maintainer accepts.

===Why the BIP 388 placeholder framing instead of inline keys?===

The placeholder framing has three advantages over inline keys:

# '''Compactness.''' Each <code>@i</code> reference encodes as 2 bytes vs 78 bytes for an inline xpub. For a 6-key policy, this saves ~456 bytes of bytecode — making the difference between fitting one engraved plate and fitting many.
# '''Separation of structure from key material.''' The Template Card contains zero key material in v0; it can be backed up independently of seeds and xpub cards. Loss or compromise of a Template Card does not compromise key secrecy.
# '''Standard alignment.''' BIP 388 already defines the placeholder framing for hardware-signer wallet-policy registration. Aligning MD's bytecode with BIP 388's framing minimizes work for wallets that already produce BIP 388 wallet policies.

===Why mandate guided recovery in the spec?===

The format's robustness story has two layers: BCH error correction (always present) and structure-aware recovery (when structural knowledge is available). The latter substantially extends the correction envelope but requires implementations to expose it. If guided recovery were optional, different MD tools would offer different recovery success rates for the same damaged input, undermining the format's reliability promise.

By specifying guided recovery as a conformance requirement, all MD tools provide consistent recovery semantics. Users with damaged backups are not at the mercy of which tool they happen to be using.

===Why no compression?===

The format already provides large implicit compression via the placeholder mechanism and tag-based encoding (~40× compression on key material vs inline xpubs; ~10× on operator names vs plaintext). For payload sizes typical of bitcoin wallet policies (≤ 60 bytes), generic compression (LZ-family) yields 5–20% additional savings — offset by dictionary overhead, decompressor complexity, and increased attack surface.

Hardware signers parsing MD-encoded policies (Coldcard, BitBox, Jade, Ledger) have memory and code-size constraints that favor direct opcode interpretation over compressed input. The chunking scheme handles arbitrary lengths, so compression's primary benefit (avoiding chunk boundaries) is moot.

If a future revision identifies compression as worth adding, it should be: (a) a dictionary of common timelock values; (b) an n-of-n implicit-thresh opcode for long <code>and_v</code> chains. Generic LZ on bytecode is not recommended.

===Why no built-in encryption?===

The Template Card contains no key material in v0; it encodes wallet structure. A finder of a Template Card learns the spending policy (e.g., timelock periods, threshold counts, the existence of cosigners) but cannot derive any private keys without also obtaining the user's seed(s).

Encrypting the Template Card is technically straightforward but introduces a new failure mode: loss of the encryption key separate from loss of the seed. Since the Template Card is already useless without the seed for actual fund recovery, the privacy gain from encryption (concealing wallet ''structure'') trades against the recovery risk (now requiring two independent secrets).

A future revision MAY define an optional encrypted Template Card variant. v0 does not include one.

===Why mandatory chunk-set identifier in chunked cards?===

Without per-chunk-set identifiers, a user with multiple wallets risks mixing chunks from different Template Cards during reassembly. The 20-bit identifier provides ~1-in-1M discrimination against accidental cross-wallet contamination, and because every chunk header carries the same CSI, mismatched chunks are rejected before any payload reassembly is attempted.

The 20-bit value is normatively derived from the encoding's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> (see §"Header") rather than drawn from a CSPRNG. This serves two purposes. First, it makes md1 bit-reproducible: two conforming encoders given the same canonical bytecode produce identical Template Card strings down to the wire bits, which lets downstream toolchains (engraving toolkits, regression-pinned vector corpora) SHA-pin md1 outputs without flake. Second, the deterministic binding doubles as the cross-chunk integrity check: decoders re-derive the CSI from the reassembled payload's <code>Md1EncodingId</code> and reject if it differs from the wire CSI carried in chunk headers. The v0.30 wire format does NOT carry a separate cross-chunk hash field — the CSI derivation IS the integrity check, and a non-conforming encoder that drew a random CSI value would produce strings unreadable by conforming decoders, so the determinism contract is self-enforcing.

For single-string Template Cards, no chunk-set identifier is needed because there are no chunks to confuse.

==Frequently Asked Questions==

===Why is MD narrower than BIP 388?===

BIP 388 admits six top-level wallet-policy shapes: <code>pkh(KEY)</code>, <code>wpkh(KEY)</code>, <code>sh(wpkh(KEY))</code>, <code>wsh(SCRIPT)</code>, <code>sh(wsh(SCRIPT))</code>, and <code>tr(KEY[, TREE])</code>. It also admits <code>sh(multi(...))</code> and <code>sh(sortedmulti(...))</code> as legacy P2SH multisig forms. MD accepts a strict subset, rejecting:

* <code>pkh(KEY)</code> — legacy P2PKH single-sig
* <code>sh(KEY)</code>, <code>sh(multi(...))</code>, <code>sh(sortedmulti(...))</code> — legacy P2SH

Rationale (three reasons, weighted):

# '''Address-prefix ambiguity creates a recovery footgun.''' Both <code>sh(multi(K, ...))</code> (legacy P2SH multisig, 2014–2017 era) and <code>sh(wsh(...))</code> (BIP 48/1' modern nested-segwit multisig) produce addresses with the <code>3...</code> prefix. A user looking at a <code>3...</code> address from cold storage often cannot disambiguate which descriptor type produced it. Engraving the wrong type would derive the wrong addresses on recovery — silent fund loss. MD eliminates this footgun by rejecting <code>sh(multi)</code> at the spec level.
# '''Engravable steel backup is overkill for legacy single-sig.''' BIP 39 seed words alone are sufficient backup for <code>pkh(KEY)</code> wallets; the policy template adds no recovery information. MD's value proposition (engravable backup of policies hard to reconstruct) doesn't apply.
# '''No deployment of new pre-segwit wallets.''' Modern hardware wallets (Coldcard, Trezor, Ledger) emit modern post-segwit forms by default. Realistic users wanting to engrave 2015-era cold storage are vanishingly few; most pre-segwit wallets have either been swept to native segwit or sit dormant.

The three reasons combine: a category with high footgun risk, low marginal recovery value, and negligible new deployment is permanently excluded by design. This is a deliberate narrowing of BIP 388, not a future deferral.

===Why is multi-leaf TapTree deferred (vs excluded)?===

(Historical context — v0.4 deferral rationale.) <code>tr(KEY, TREE)</code> with multi-leaf TapTree (BIP 388 §"Taproot tree") is a substantive feature requiring its own design pass: TapTree depth/balancing rules, leaf-wrapper subset re-evaluation (Coldcard tap-leaf subset is currently restrictive), per-leaf miniscript context validation. Deferring to a future MD revision (v0.5+) keeps the v0.4 release focused. Unlike the legacy exclusions above, multi-leaf TapTree IS planned admission.

===Why does v0.5 admit multi-leaf TapTree?===

The v0.4 deferral was scope-driven, not design-driven. Multi-leaf TapTree was always a planned admission target; v0.5 ships it because:

# The BIP 388 modern-segwit surface (closed at v0.4 with <code>wpkh</code>, <code>sh(wpkh)</code>, <code>sh(wsh)</code>) is now stable, freeing engineering bandwidth for the taproot tree work.
# The peek-before-recurse + depth-gate hardening pattern from v0.4's <code>sh(...)</code> restriction matrix transfers directly to <code>TapTree</code>'s recursive framing — the security review surface is small.
# BIP 341's <code>TAPROOT_CONTROL_MAX_NODE_COUNT = 128</code> provides an upstream-defined ceiling that requires no MD-specific tightening, simplifying the spec.
# rust-miniscript's <code>TapTree::leaves()</code> + <code>TapTree::combine</code> APIs make the encoder/decoder a thin shim over upstream's depth-aware tree representation.

v0.5 does NOT broaden the per-leaf miniscript subset — each leaf is admissible on the same terms as v0.4.x's single-leaf <code>tr(KEY, leaf)</code> admits. The <code>validate_tap_leaf_subset</code> gate is unchanged.

===Why is <code>bare(SCRIPT)</code> rejected?===

BIP 388 itself excludes <code>bare(SCRIPT)</code> (pre-2014 raw script output type, no address). MD inherits this exclusion.

===Why no inline xpubs (foreign keys)?===

MD's <code>@i</code> placeholder framing assumes named keys provided separately at recovery time (BIP 388 wallet-policy structure). Inline xpubs (descriptor-codec reserved tags <code>0x24</code>–<code>0x31</code>) would change the recovery model: the engraved card would carry key material, defeating the steel-engravable backup form factor's value (key material is in the seeds, not the engraved card).

===What about <code>tr(KEY)</code> single-sig taproot?===

Single-key taproot (<code>tr(KEY)</code>) and single-leaf taproot (<code>tr(KEY, single-leaf-script)</code>) are both supported and have been since v0.2. As of v0.5, these are degenerate cases of the full multi-leaf admission: single-leaf is simply a tree of depth zero (no <code>TapTree</code> inner node), and keypath-only is an absent script-tree position. The bytecode encoding for both forms is UNCHANGED from v0.4.x — v0.5 is wire-additive, not wire-breaking, for these cases.

===Why is the HRP <code>md</code> rather than something more descriptive?===

Matches the 2-character convention of BIP 93's <code>ms</code> HRP for codex32. Shorter HRPs leave more capacity in the BCH-bounded data part for policy bytecode. The earlier <code>wdm</code> HRP was renamed to <code>md</code> at v0.3.0 — see CHANGELOG.

===Why is the family-stable generator string <code>"md-codec X.Y"</code> rather than the full crate version?===

Family-stability across patch versions: any v0.4.x build regenerating <code>v0.2.json</code> produces a byte-identical SHA, so downstream conformance suites pinning the SHA see no churn within a v0.4.x line. Patch-version traceability is preserved in <code>gen_vectors --output</code>'s stderr log. Family token bumps at minor version boundaries (v0.3 → v0.4 shifts <code>"md-codec 0.3"</code> to <code>"md-codec 0.4"</code>).

==Backwards Compatibility==

MD is a new format; there is no prior version to be compatible with.

MD does not conflict with existing standards:

* '''BIP 39 / SLIP 39 / BIP 93 (codex32):''' MD uses a different HRP (<code>md</code> vs <code>ms</code>), so an MD string is never confused with a codex32 seed share. The bech32 checksums are computed over the HRP plus data, providing cryptographic domain separation.
* '''BIP 173 / BIP 350 (bech32 / bech32m addresses):''' MD uses neither <code>bc</code>/<code>tb</code>/<code>bcrt</code> HRPs nor the bech32m generator constant; addresses cannot be confused with MD strings.
* '''BIP 380 (output descriptors):''' BIP 380 descriptors do not contain the <code>@</code> character, so a BIP 380 descriptor cannot be confused with a BIP 388 wallet policy, and neither can be confused with MD-encoded bytecode (which is binary, not a descriptor string).
* '''BIP 388 (wallet policies):''' MD ''encodes'' BIP 388 wallet policies. Round-trip with BIP 388 canonical form is a stated invariant.

MD v0 readers MUST reject MD strings with newer format-version bytes (loud failure; recommend the user obtain a newer MD tool). v1+ readers MUST accept v0 strings (graceful upgrade).

'''Wire-format breaks on the v0.x evolution path.''' Three breaks shape the v0.30 wire format (historical context):

* '''v0.x ≤ 0.9 → v0.10 (path-divergence support).''' v0.x ≤ 0.9 lossily flattened policies with divergent per-<code>@N</code> origin paths to a single shared path, so <code>decode(encode(p))</code> could differ from <code>p</code> for any policy where cosigners derived xpubs from different paths. v0.10 closed that bug by reclaiming bit 3 of the byte-aligned bytecode header as a divergent-paths flag and adding a per-<code>@N</code> path block. Pre-v0.10 decoders rejected v0.10 divergent-paths encodings cleanly via <code>Error::ReservedBitsSet</code>.
* '''v0.x ≤ 0.10 → v0.11 (bit-packed wire-format reset).''' v0.11 replaced the byte-aligned bytecode framing (1-byte header, 1-byte path-decl tags, byte-aligned operator tags) with a packed 5-bit bit stream, eliminating per-section framing tags entirely; fingerprints, xpubs, and per-<code>@N</code> overrides moved into the §"TLV section". The path-divergence fix from v0.10 was preserved (signaled by header bit 4 directly, with no framing tag); see §"Origin path declaration". v0.x ≤ 0.10 decoders could not read v0.11 encodings, and vice versa; the change was a clean break with no compat layer.
* '''v0.x → v0.30 (wire-format redesign).''' v0.30 widens the bytecode primary tag space from 5-bit to 6-bit (5 hash/literal operators promoted to primary), widens the header version field from 3-bit to 4-bit, relocates the chunked-flag to bit 0 of the first 5-bit symbol for in-band auto-dispatch, packs multi-family children as raw kiw-bit indices (no per-child tags), retires the <code>tr()</code> NUMS sentinel in favor of an explicit <code>is_nums</code> flag (restoring <code>kiw = ⌈log₂(n)⌉</code>), and refines the decoder error taxonomy. v0.x payloads fed to a v0.30 decoder raise <code>Error::WireVersionMismatch</code> cleanly per the auto-dispatch trace in §"Auto-dispatch and safe rejection". This is a clean break with no compat layer.

Users who computed PolicyIds on divergent-path policies under v0.x ≤ 0.9 SHOULD re-engrave under v0.10+. Users who recovered policies from v0.x ≤ 0.29 Template Cards SHOULD re-engrave under v0.30; v0.30 decoders cannot read pre-v0.30 encodings.

==Test Vectors==

The v0.30 reference test corpus lives at <code>crates/md-codec/tests/vectors/</code> in the reference implementation. Each vector is a tuple of three plain-text files sharing a common stem <code>{name}</code>:

{| class="wikitable"
! File !! Contents
|-
| <code>{name}.template</code> || The input BIP 388 wallet-policy template (e.g., <code>wsh(multi(2,@0/<0;1>/*,@1/<0;1>/*))</code>).
|-
| <code>{name}.descriptor.json</code> || The post-decode AST: a JSON serialization of the <code>Descriptor</code> struct (n, path_decl, use_site_path, tree, tlv).
|-
| <code>{name}.phrase.txt</code> || The md1 string produced by encoding the template (BCH-checksummed codex32 output).
|-
| <code>{name}.bytes.hex</code> || The raw bit-packed payload bytes (hex), pre-codex32-wrap. Used for byte-level cross-implementation checks.
|}

A loader (<code>crates/md-codec/tests/vectors/manifest.rs</code>) enumerates the corpus at build time. Conformance tests round-trip each vector: <code>encode(template) == phrase</code> and <code>decode(phrase) == descriptor</code>. Independent implementations SHOULD verify against the committed file tuples for the MD version they target.

